To use Word Wrap for Excel through Delphi code, you can follow these steps:

1. First, you need to add the Excel type library to your Delphi project. To do this, go to the menu item Project -> Import Type Library, and then select "Microsoft Excel XX.0 Object Library" (where XX is the version number).

2. After that, you can include the Excel type library in your code by adding the following line to your Delphi unit:

uses Excel_TLB;

3. To enable Word Wrap for a cell in Excel, you can use the following code:

var
  Excel: _Application;
  Workbook: _Workbook;
  Worksheet: _Worksheet;
begin
  Excel := CoExcelApplication.Create;
  Excel.Visible := True;
  Workbook := Excel.Workbooks.Add(EmptyParam, 0);
  Worksheet := Workbook.Worksheets[1] as _Worksheet;
  Worksheet.Cells[1,1].WrapText := true;
end;

4. In this code example, we create a new Excel application object, make it visible, and add a new workbook. Then we access the first worksheet and set the WrapText property of cell A1 to true, which enables Word Wrap for that cell.

5. You can modify this code to suit your needs by selecting a different cell or range of cells, or by setting other properties on the worksheet or workbook objects.

6. Don't forget to free any Excel objects you create by calling their corresponding Release methods or by assigning them to nil.

Note: To use the Excel type library, you must have Microsoft Excel installed on your computer. Also, be aware that automating Excel through Delphi code can be slow and resource-intensive, so you should use it sparingly and optimize your code as much as possible.

Range := wb.WorkSheets[1].Range[wb.WorkSheets[1].Cells[1, 1],
                                  wb.WorkSheets[1].Cells[RowCount+1, ColCount+1]];
Word wrap the range pasted above from Delphi code

To word wrap the range pasted above from Delphi code, you can use the following code:

```
var
  Excel: _Application;
  Workbook: _Workbook;
  Worksheet: _Worksheet;
  Range: Range;
begin
  Excel := CoExcelApplication.Create;
  Excel.Visible := True;
  Workbook := Excel.Workbooks.Open('C:\Path\To\Workbook.xlsx');
  Worksheet := Workbook.Worksheets[1] as _Worksheet;

  // Get the range you want to apply the word wrap to
  Range := Worksheet.Range[Worksheet.Cells[1, 1], Worksheet.Cells[RowCount+1, ColCount+1]];

  // Set the word wrap property of the range to true
  Range.WrapText := True;

  // Close the workbook and release the objects
  Workbook.Close(False, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);
  Excel.Quit;
  Excel := nil;
  Workbook := nil;
  Worksheet := nil;
  Range := nil;
end;
```

In the code above, we first create a new Excel application object, open the workbook, and get the worksheet we want to work with.

Next, we get the range of cells we want to apply the word wrap to by using the `Range` property of the worksheet object. We use the `Cells` property to specify the starting and ending cells of the range.

Finally, we set the `WrapText` property of the `Range` object to `True` to enable word wrap for the cells in the range.

After we're done, we close the workbook and release the objects to free up memory.

To set Wrap text to false for an entire worksheet in Delphi 7, you can use the following code:

```delphi
var
  Excel: _Application;
  Workbook: _Workbook;
  Worksheet: _Worksheet;
  i,j : integer;
begin
  Excel := CoExcelApplication.Create;
  Excel.Visible := True;
  Workbook := Excel.Workbooks.Open('C:\Path\To\Workbook.xlsx');
  Worksheet := Workbook.Worksheets[1] as _Worksheet;

  // Loop through all cells in the worksheet and set the wrap text property to false
  for i := 1 to Worksheet.UsedRange.Rows.Count do
  begin
    for j := 1 to Worksheet.UsedRange.Columns.Count do
    begin
      Worksheet.Cells[i, j].WrapText := false;
    end;
  end;

  // Save and close the workbook, and release the objects
  Workbook.Save;
  Workbook.Close(False, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);
  Excel.Quit;
  Excel := nil;
  Workbook := nil;
  Worksheet := nil;
end;
```

In the code above, we first create a new Excel application object, open the workbook, and get the worksheet we want to work with.

Next, we loop through all cells in the worksheet using two nested `for` loops. For each cell, we set the `WrapText` property to `false`.

Finally, we save and close the workbook, and release the Excel objects to free up memory.

Note that this code can be slow for large worksheets with many cells. In such cases, it's better to use the `Range` object and specify the range of cells you want to modify instead of looping through all the cells in the worksheet.

To encrypt an Excel file with a password from Delphi, you can use the following code:

```delphi
var
  Excel: _Application;
  Workbook: _Workbook;
begin
  Excel := CoExcelApplication.Create;
  Excel.Visible := True;
  Workbook := Excel.Workbooks.Open('C:\Path\To\Workbook.xlsx');

  // Encrypt the workbook and set a password
  Workbook.Password := 'MyPassword';
  Workbook.SaveAs('C:\Path\To\EncryptedWorkbook.xlsx', EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam,
    True, False, xlNoChange, EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);

  // Close the original workbook and release the objects
  Workbook.Saved := True;
  Workbook.Close(False, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);
  Excel.Quit;
  Excel := nil;
  Workbook := nil;
end;
```

In the code above, we first create a new Excel application object and open the workbook we want to encrypt.

Next, we set a password for the workbook by assigning a value to the `Password` property of the `Workbook` object. Note that the password is case-sensitive.

After that, we save the encrypted workbook using the `SaveAs` method of the `Workbook` object. We specify the file path of the encrypted workbook, set the `PasswordEncryptionProvider` parameter to `True`, and leave all other parameters as `EmptyParam` except for the `PasswordEncryptionAlgorithm` parameter, which we set to `xlNoChange`.

Finally, we close the original workbook, set the `Saved` property to `True` to avoid being prompted to save changes, and release the Excel objects to free up memory.

Note that passwords can be easily cracked, so it's recommended to use other security measures such as file permissions or encryption outside of Excel to protect sensitive data.

To highlight column headers in Excel from Delphi code, you can use the following code:

```delphi
var
  Excel: _Application;
  Workbook: _Workbook;
  Worksheet: _Worksheet;
  Range: Range;
begin
  Excel := CoExcelApplication.Create;
  Excel.Visible := True;
  Workbook := Excel.Workbooks.Open('C:\Path\To\Workbook.xlsx');
  Worksheet := Workbook.Worksheets[1] as _Worksheet;

  // Get the range of cells containing the column headers
  Range := Worksheet.Range[Worksheet.Cells[1, 1], Worksheet.Cells[1, ColCount]];

  // Set the background color of the range to a light gray
  Range.Interior.Color := $F2F2F2;

  // Set the font color of the range to black
  Range.Font.Color := clBlack;
  Range.Font.Bold := True;

  // Close the workbook and release the objects
  Workbook.Close(False, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);
  Excel.Quit;
  Excel := nil;
  Workbook := nil;
  Worksheet := nil;
  Range := nil;
end;
```

In the code above, we first create a new Excel application object, open the workbook, and get the worksheet we want to work with.

Next, we get the range of cells containing the column headers by using the `Range` property of the worksheet object. We use the `Cells` property to specify the starting and ending cells of the range.

Then, we set the background color of the range to a light gray using the `Interior.Color` property of the `Range` object.

After that, we set the font color of the range to black and make the text bold using the `Font.Color` and `Font.Bold` properties of the `Range` object.

Finally, we close the workbook and release the Excel objects to free up memory.

Note that you can customize the color and other formatting properties of the column headers by modifying the code above.

