The behavior you described might occur if the `ReadOnlyRecommended` property of the workbook has been set to `True`. This makes Excel display a prompt to open the file read-only, even after the correct password has been entered.

To avoid the prompt and allow the user to edit the workbook after entering the correct password, you can set the `ReadOnlyRecommended` property to `False` before encrypting the workbook:

```delphi
var
  Excel: _Application;
  Workbook: _Workbook;
begin
  Excel := CoExcelApplication.Create;
  Excel.Visible := True;
  Workbook := Excel.Workbooks.Open('C:\Path\To\Workbook.xlsx');

  // Disable read-only recommended mode to avoid a prompt after encryption
  Workbook.ReadOnlyRecommended := False;

  // Encrypt the workbook with a password
  Workbook.Password := 'MyPassword';
  Workbook.SaveAs('C:\Path\To\EncryptedWorkbook.xlsx', EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam,
    True, False, xlNoChange, EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);

  // Close the original workbook and release the objects
  Workbook.Saved := True;
  Workbook.Close(False, EmptyParam, EmptyParam);
  Excel.Quit;
  Excel := nil;
  Workbook := nil;
end;
```

In the code above, we first open the workbook and then set the `ReadOnlyRecommended` property to `False`. This will prevent the read-only prompt from appearing later.

After that, we encrypt the workbook with a password using the `Password` property of the `Workbook` object. We also use the `SaveAs` method to save the encrypted workbook under a new file name.

Finally, we close the original workbook, set the `Saved` property to `True` to avoid being prompted to save changes, and release the Excel objects to free up memory.

Note that passwords can be easily cracked, so it's recommended to use other security measures such as file permissions or encryption outside of Excel to protect sensitive data.
